When I go to Home Depot I use

00:28:04.975 --> 00:28:09.160
the Home Depot units.
All right, so here are the two

00:28:09.160 --> 00:28:12.861
accelerations.
Let's take the ratio of those

00:28:12.861 --> 00:28:16.524
two numbers.
Now, the apple's acceleration,

00:28:16.524 --> 00:28:19.079
all of you guys know,
right?

00:28:19.079 --> 00:28:22.430
It's the one thing we know from
day one: 9.8 meters per second

00:28:22.430 --> 00:28:24.794
squared.
Acceleration of the Moon,

00:28:24.794 --> 00:28:28.695
how am I going to find that?
So, I need an idea on how to

00:28:28.695 --> 00:28:30.940
find the acceleration of the
Moon.

00:28:30.940 --> 00:28:36.089
Anybody from this corner of the
room, on the top.

00:28:36.089 --> 00:28:38.360
How do I find the acceleration
of the Moon towards the Earth?

00:28:38.360 --> 00:28:40.330
What will I have to know?
Yes?

00:28:40.330 --> 00:28:41.675
Student: v^(2)/R.
Professor Ramamurti

00:28:41.675 --> 00:28:43.920
Shankar: Very good.
That's all I wanted from you.

00:28:43.920 --> 00:28:47.512
We'll fill in the blanks but
it's v^(2)/R,

00:28:47.512 --> 00:28:51.031
and R is this quarter of
a million miles,

00:28:51.031 --> 00:28:54.099
and v is the orbital
velocity.

00:28:54.099 --> 00:28:56.970
You may not know the orbital
velocity of the Moon but you

00:28:56.970 --> 00:28:59.327
