But maybe it should be just the
two meters from which I release

00:52:48.762 --> 00:52:50.727
it.
Somehow he knew you have to

00:52:50.727 --> 00:52:53.989
measure the distance from the
center of the Earth.

00:52:53.989 --> 00:53:00.340
So, it is not clear for the
purposes of gravitation.

00:53:00.340 --> 00:53:03.174
In other words,
originally Newton had a law of

00:53:03.174 --> 00:53:06.889
gravitation between two point
objects, namely point-like.

00:53:06.889 --> 00:53:09.702
The distance between them is
unambiguously the distance

00:53:09.702 --> 00:53:11.889
between the points,
and he got this law.

00:53:11.889 --> 00:53:15.538
But in the end,
he wants to apply it to the

00:53:15.538 --> 00:53:18.800
Earth and the apple;
they are close enough for you.

00:53:18.800 --> 00:53:21.731
You cannot pretend the Earth
looks like a point from where I

00:53:21.731 --> 00:53:23.450
am.
It looks like a big, fat thing.

00:53:23.450 --> 00:53:26.567
You cannot say it's point-like.
So, what you really should do

00:53:26.567 --> 00:53:29.588
is divide the Earth into tiny
pieces, each one of which is

00:53:29.588 --> 00:53:32.467
point-like,
find the force on each from

00:53:32.467 --> 00:53:35.554
each chunk of the Earth,
using this law,

00:53:35.554 --> 00:53:37.994
and add it up.
And if you're lucky,

00:53:37.994 --> 00:53:41.388
it will look as if all the pull
is coming from one point at the

00:53:41.388 --> 00:53:44.070
center, carrying the entire mass
of the Earth.

00:53:44.070 --> 00:53:48.539
So, what branch of mathematics
do you have to use to get that

00:53:48.539 --> 00:53:50.119
result?
Yes?

00:53:50.119 --> 00:53:52.602
Student: [inaudible]
Professor Ramamurti

00:53:52.602 --> 00:53:54.730
Shankar: What branch of
mathematics?

00:53:54.730 --> 00:53:58.477
What kind of calculus?
Students: [inaudible]

00:53:58.477 --> 00:53:59.312
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: Had it been

00:53:59.312 --> 00:54:01.250
invented?
No.

00:54:01.250 --> 00:54:04.630
So, he had to then invent
integral calculus also.

00:54:04.630 --> 00:54:08.059
So, if he felt that no one
around him was doing any work,

00:54:08.059 --> 00:54:11.304
it was probably justified
because they just dumped the

00:54:11.304 --> 00:54:13.570
whole thing on this kid and
said,

00:54:13.570 --> 00:54:16.521
why don't you do Integral--?
That's why it took him a long

00:54:16.521 --> 00:54:18.489
time to verify,
using integrals,

00:54:18.489 --> 00:54:22.489
that the sphere behaves like a
point particle at the center.

00:54:22.489 --> 00:54:25.387
He knew it works because all
these numbers couldn't be all

00:54:25.387 --> 00:54:27.369
the coincidences or not
coincidences.

00:54:27.369 --> 00:54:30.471
He believed it worked but he
had not found a way to show it,

00:54:30.471 --> 00:54:32.679
and that's what held back a
publication.

00:54:32.679 --> 00:54:34.699
Okay, that's another rare
behavior.

00:54:34.699 --> 00:54:37.499
Okay, anyway,
I come to this problem and I

00:54:37.499 --> 00:54:41.869
say I want to apply it not near
the Earth but arbitrarily far.

00:54:41.869 --> 00:54:45.694
Near the Earth the force is
-mg, but far from the

00:54:45.694 --> 00:54:50.518
Earth, many, many miles away,
the force is really what we

00:54:50.518 --> 00:54:55.360
wrote here, is -GMm/r^(2)
times r,

00:54:55.360 --> 00:54:57.360
unit vector in the radial
direction.

00:54:57.360 --> 00:55:01.998
The first thing you can check
is that this is actually a

00:55:01.998 --> 00:55:06.460
conservative force.
I'm going to give this to you.

00:55:06.460 --> 00:55:08.429
I don't have time to do that.
In other words,

00:55:08.429 --> 00:55:11.828
write this r-hat if you
like, with an r divided

00:55:11.828 --> 00:55:14.829
by one more r on the
bottom, we don't care.

00:55:14.829 --> 00:55:22.470
And that can be returned as
-GMm times I times

00:55:22.470 --> 00:55:27.910
x/r^(3) + J times
y/r^(3).

00:55:27.910 --> 00:55:31.829
Right?
I just wrote the vector

00:55:31.829 --> 00:55:33.550
r in terms of x
and y.

00:55:33.550 --> 00:55:36.720
So the x component of this
force is x/r^(3);

00:55:36.720 --> 00:55:40.482
the y is y/r^(3).
r is just square root of x^(2)

00:55:40.482 --> 00:55:42.958
+ y^(2).
So maybe you can tell me,

00:55:42.958 --> 00:55:47.250
what should I do to check that
this is a conservative force?

00:55:47.250 --> 00:55:53.006
Student: Use that
formula and [inaudible]

00:55:53.006 --> 00:55:58.150
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: Yes.

00:55:58.150 --> 00:56:00.619
I will repeat what he said;
that's the correct answer.

00:56:00.619 --> 00:56:03.207
I must take the x
component of this,

00:56:03.207 --> 00:56:05.610
take the y partial
derivative,

00:56:05.610 --> 00:56:07.865
the y component of this,
take an x partial

00:56:07.865 --> 00:56:09.739
derivatives.
You guys should do that.

00:56:09.739 --> 00:56:12.892
When you take the derivative of
something like 1/r^(3),

00:56:12.892 --> 00:56:15.321
you should first take the
r derivative of

00:56:15.321 --> 00:56:17.239
r^(3),
and then take the x

00:56:17.239 --> 00:56:19.280
derivative of r or the
y derivative.

00:56:19.280 --> 00:56:21.481
Using the Chain Rule of
calculus, you'll find the two

00:56:21.481 --> 00:56:23.400
agree.
So, we know it's conservative.

00:56:23.400 --> 00:56:27.011
That's the power of the result.
So, all you have to do is guess

00:56:27.011 --> 00:56:29.670
what potential could have led to
this force.

00:56:29.670 --> 00:56:33.340
So I say, okay,
let's put the Sun here.

00:56:33.340 --> 00:56:35.469
Let me move along the x
axis.

00:56:35.469 --> 00:56:38.486
The force, along the x
axis, looks like

00:56:38.486 --> 00:56:41.905
-GMm/x^(2) because
x is just r,

00:56:41.905 --> 00:56:44.519
if you're moving in this
direction.

00:56:44.519 --> 00:56:46.840
In the other direction that's
r, but let me just move

00:56:46.840 --> 00:56:48.933
along the x direction.
I ask myself,

00:56:48.933 --> 00:56:52.965
what function has a property
that minus a derivative of that,

00:56:52.965 --> 00:56:55.989
with respect to x,
looks like this?

00:56:55.989 --> 00:56:59.080
That's a Mickey-Mouse calculus
problem.

00:56:59.080 --> 00:57:01.710
It's just -1/x.
Okay?

00:57:01.710 --> 00:57:05.219
Minus the derivative of
-1/x is -1/x^(2).

00:57:05.219 --> 00:57:08.860
Therefore, x is
r, in general.

00:57:08.860 --> 00:57:12.350
The U that you want for
gravitation looks like this.

00:57:16.039 --> 00:57:20.773
So, gravitational potential
energy for problems arbitrarily

00:57:20.773 --> 00:57:23.630
far from the center of this
mass,

00:57:23.630 --> 00:57:26.210
not near just the surface of
the Earth but wherever you go,

00:57:26.210 --> 00:57:28.480
in any gravitational problem,
this is U.

00:57:32.210 --> 00:57:34.185
You can check but if you took
this U,

00:57:34.185 --> 00:57:36.070
here's what I'm telling you
guys to do.

00:57:36.070 --> 00:57:37.809
If you're really--.
Did I miss something?

00:57:37.809 --> 00:57:39.940
Student: Shouldn't that
be positive?

00:57:39.940 --> 00:57:41.780
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: No.

00:57:41.780 --> 00:57:46.630
Let's see.
If you took the r

00:57:46.630 --> 00:57:50.630
derivative of this,
1/r is r to the

00:57:50.630 --> 00:57:52.692
-1;
the derivative of that will

00:57:52.692 --> 00:57:55.858
make it +1/r^(2).
But you're really supposed to

00:57:55.858 --> 00:57:58.170
take minus the derivative of
U;

00:57:58.170 --> 00:58:02.397
and that'll be the right thing.
So, this is the potential

00:58:02.397 --> 00:58:08.699
energy, which will be negative.
So, what am I claiming?

00:58:08.699 --> 00:58:11.441
I'm claiming that if you got
the Sun and you got some other

00:58:11.441 --> 00:58:15.967
planet moving around it,
the following quantity will not

00:58:15.967 --> 00:58:22.030
change, which is Â½ mv^(2) -
GmM/r is a constant.

00:58:32.530 --> 00:58:35.500
Now, take an object moving near
the Earth.

00:58:35.500 --> 00:58:39.010
I gave you a different rule.
I said near the Earth.

00:58:39.010 --> 00:58:45.671
What did I say the rule was?
The constant is Â½ mv^(2) +

00:58:45.671 --> 00:58:49.360
mgh.
Kinetic energy looks right;

00:58:49.360 --> 00:58:51.519
potential energy looks really
wrong.

00:58:51.519 --> 00:58:54.800
There seem to be two
definitions of potential energy.

00:58:54.800 --> 00:58:56.370
They don't even agree in sign.

00:58:59.610 --> 00:59:04.795
So, what's going on?
What's the way out of this

00:59:04.795 --> 00:59:07.579
problem I'm in?
Do you have any idea?

00:59:07.579 --> 00:59:12.400
Student: You have to
have g by some vector.

00:59:12.400 --> 00:59:13.713
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: G,

00:59:13.713 --> 00:59:15.351
you mean, or g?
Student: [inaudible]

00:59:15.351 --> 00:59:16.647
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: Oh,

00:59:16.647 --> 00:59:18.630
that's not a bad idea.
Suppose I do that.

00:59:18.630 --> 00:59:21.752
That's a very good idea.
So, let me write that as

00:59:21.752 --> 00:59:25.768
GMm over
R^(2)_E times

00:59:25.768 --> 00:59:28.860
h.
That's a good plan.

00:59:28.860 --> 00:59:32.345
But you notice this cannot
possibly equal that because

00:59:32.345 --> 00:59:33.990
that's negative,
right?

00:59:33.990 --> 00:59:34.980
This is positive.

00:59:39.530 --> 00:59:41.730
Any way to reconcile these?
Yes?

00:59:41.730 --> 00:59:44.263
Student: Well,
differences because the first

00:59:44.263 --> 00:59:47.303
one is for different values of
force, while the second one is

00:59:47.303 --> 00:59:48.840
assuming a constant.
Professor Ramamurti

00:59:48.840 --> 00:59:50.656
Shankar: I agree.
But no, the constant is

00:59:50.656 --> 00:59:54.299
certainly--It's true that near
the Earth we treat it as a

00:59:54.299 --> 00:59:56.791
constant.
But if I took the formula value

00:59:56.791 --> 00:59:59.716
for every distance and I
specialized it to the problem

00:59:59.716 --> 01:00:02.274
near the Earth,
it's got to agree with the

01:00:02.274 --> 01:00:04.139
problem near the Earth,
right?

01:00:04.139 --> 01:00:07.118
The bigger formula should
embrace or enclose a smaller

01:00:07.118 --> 01:00:10.618
formula.
Student: Maybe we should

01:00:10.618 --> 01:00:14.219
say the radii equal to the first
one.

01:00:14.219 --> 01:00:14.728
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: Yes,

01:00:14.728 --> 01:00:16.016
I will do that.
In other words,

01:00:16.016 --> 01:00:19.999
I grant you I'm willing to put
R_E here,

01:00:19.999 --> 01:00:21.663
right?
But there is no way this

01:00:21.663 --> 01:00:24.222
expression and this can match
because they're not even of the

01:00:24.222 --> 01:00:25.952
right sign.
You don't even have to think

01:00:25.952 --> 01:00:28.907
more than that.
They cannot be right as they

01:00:28.907 --> 01:00:30.840
are.
Yes?

01:00:30.840 --> 01:00:35.276
Student: Maybe try to
explain h in terms of

01:00:35.276 --> 01:00:36.599
radii.
Like the difference in

01:00:36.599 --> 01:00:37.634
[inaudible]
Professor Ramamurti

01:00:37.634 --> 01:00:38.920
Shankar: No,
h is the number of

01:00:38.920 --> 01:00:41.329
meters above the ground.
You put the number in.

01:00:41.329 --> 01:00:44.943
Look, most of your escape
routes don't work because you're

01:00:44.943 --> 01:00:48.810
trying to get a positive number
to equal a negative number.

01:00:53.070 --> 01:00:55.267
Yes?
Student: [inaudible]

01:00:55.267 --> 01:00:57.559
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: Thank you.

01:00:57.559 --> 01:01:00.487
I didn't know I was going home
for lunch, because I was not

01:01:00.487 --> 01:01:02.909
going to proceed until I got the
right answer.

01:01:02.909 --> 01:01:06.057
The right answer is,
when you define a potential,

01:01:06.057 --> 01:01:09.729
there is a freedom to add a
constant to the definition of

01:01:09.729 --> 01:01:12.107
the potential.
If you look at every theorem,

01:01:12.107 --> 01:01:14.255
everything I derived,
including the stuff I've hidden

01:01:14.255 --> 01:01:15.897
under the board,
U_1 -

01:01:15.897 --> 01:01:18.039
U_2 is what enters
everywhere;

01:01:18.039 --> 01:01:19.659
the change in kinetic energy is
U_1 -

01:01:19.659 --> 01:01:22.536
U_2.
Therefore, one has a freedom in

01:01:22.536 --> 01:01:26.969
defining the potential to add a
constant, and what has happened

01:01:26.969 --> 01:01:31.260
is that the person working with
this potential and the person

01:01:31.260 --> 01:01:35.550
working with this potential have
not taken the same reference

01:01:35.550 --> 01:01:38.464
point.
This person working near the

01:01:38.464 --> 01:01:42.504
Earth said, let me choose for
convenience the potential at

01:01:42.504 --> 01:01:46.099
height equal to 0 to be 0,
because that's a natural point

01:01:46.099 --> 01:01:50.500
for me.
What about this person here?

01:01:50.500 --> 01:01:52.159
Yes?
Student: Potential is 0.

01:01:52.159 --> 01:01:54.174
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: He's saying

01:01:54.174 --> 01:01:56.408
potential is 0 at infinity
because when you're doing

01:01:56.408 --> 01:01:58.331
celestial mechanics,
here's one object,

01:01:58.331 --> 01:02:01.043
other objects of various
distances, infinity is rather an

01:02:01.043 --> 01:02:03.548
interesting point.
You go infinitely far from it,

01:02:03.548 --> 01:02:06.480
no potential energy.
So, the two of them differ by a

01:02:06.480 --> 01:02:09.610
constant.
That's the reason why.

01:02:09.610 --> 01:02:12.556
And the constant can easily
overturn a quantity that's

01:02:12.556 --> 01:02:15.170
negative, and bring it up to
positive values.

01:02:15.170 --> 01:02:19.507
So, except for that constant,
once I add a certain constant,

01:02:19.507 --> 01:02:22.981
everything should work out.
So, I will show you that it

01:02:22.981 --> 01:02:24.140
does.
Okay?

01:02:24.140 --> 01:02:28.496
Then, everything will be fine.
Maybe there are two ways to do

01:02:28.496 --> 01:02:30.416
it;
I'm on two minds on how to show

01:02:30.416 --> 01:02:32.829
the two ways.
I'll try one method.

01:02:32.829 --> 01:02:38.151
Let's take the answer that's
valid for all distances,

01:02:38.151 --> 01:02:41.060
right?
That's the celestial formula.

01:02:41.060 --> 01:02:44.478
Forget all the constants.
It looks like -1/r,

01:02:44.478 --> 01:02:47.261
do you agree?
Some blah-blah-blah constant,

01:02:47.261 --> 01:02:49.871
divided by r.
So, it's a graph that looks

01:02:49.871 --> 01:02:52.266
like this.
It blows up to minus infinity

01:02:52.266 --> 01:02:55.647
when r goes to 0,
and it goes to 0 when r

01:02:55.647 --> 01:02:58.606
goes to infinity.
This is the formula for

01:02:58.606 --> 01:03:02.909
U, for a person who says
U = 0 at infinity.

01:03:02.909 --> 01:03:05.916
Now, let's look at the formula,
in the neighborhood of the

01:03:05.916 --> 01:03:07.130
surface of the Earth.

01:03:10.340 --> 01:03:11.880
Here is where we are most of
the time.

01:03:17.090 --> 01:03:21.428
So, if I shift my 0 to here,
then by design,

01:03:21.428 --> 01:03:27.179
I've made U to be 0 on
the surface of the Earth.

01:03:27.179 --> 01:03:30.344
Then, let me also measure the
new coordinate this way,

01:03:30.344 --> 01:03:32.971
called h,
which is the radial distance

01:03:32.971 --> 01:03:35.300
away from the
R_E.

01:03:35.300 --> 01:03:38.800
This is R_E,
this is R_E +

01:03:38.800 --> 01:03:41.240
h.
Then, I blow up this box.

01:03:41.240 --> 01:03:44.681
What do you find?
I blow up the box with my newly

01:03:44.681 --> 01:03:46.656
shifted origin.
Here is h,

01:03:46.656 --> 01:03:50.299
and here is the potential
energy, looking like a straight

01:03:50.299 --> 01:03:52.670
line.
And if you're lucky,

01:03:52.670 --> 01:03:57.019
the slope of the straight line
should be what?

01:03:57.019 --> 01:04:00.380
What should be the slope,
so we can reconcile everything?

01:04:05.340 --> 01:04:08.070
If a function is a straight
line, it has a certain slope.

01:04:08.070 --> 01:04:10.456
What's the y coordinate,
slope times the x

01:04:10.456 --> 01:04:11.780
coordinate.
Yes?

01:04:11.780 --> 01:04:12.619
Student: g
Professor Ramamurti

01:04:12.619 --> 01:04:14.570
Shankar: Not g.
Yes?

01:04:14.570 --> 01:04:15.725
Student: mg
Professor Ramamurti

01:04:15.725 --> 01:04:17.368
Shankar: mg.
If it's mg,

01:04:17.368 --> 01:04:20.110
if that's a slope,
mg times h would

01:04:20.110 --> 01:04:22.820
be the function you are drawing.
Right?

01:04:22.820 --> 01:04:24.400
So, that's all I have to show
you.

01:04:24.400 --> 01:04:26.658
And I will show that that's
what happens,

01:04:26.658 --> 01:04:29.353
and then we are set.
So, let's take the master

01:04:29.353 --> 01:04:31.330
formula for the potential
energy;

01:04:31.330 --> 01:04:38.219
write it as GMm.
Let's apply it to a distance;

01:04:38.219 --> 01:04:42.530
near the Earth it's r +
h.

01:04:42.530 --> 01:04:45.130
That's what we're trying to do,
right?

01:04:45.130 --> 01:04:54.208
Now, so, you must solve that
expression as -GMm over

01:04:54.208 --> 01:05:01.493
r times (1 + h/r).
That is just a rewriting of

01:05:01.493 --> 01:05:04.486
this.
And you can write that--I'm

01:05:04.486 --> 01:05:07.364
sorry, I apologize.
Do you know what's wrong with

01:05:07.364 --> 01:05:09.340
what I wrote?
This is not r + h.

01:05:09.340 --> 01:05:10.960
What should I be really putting
here?

01:05:10.960 --> 01:05:11.740
[Replaces all small "r"s in the
paragraph above with

01:05:11.740 --> 01:05:12.491
R_E]
Students: [inaudible]

01:05:12.491 --> 01:05:13.226
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: Radius of the

01:05:13.226 --> 01:05:14.747
Earth.
So, I don't know how you're

01:05:14.747 --> 01:05:17.670
going to correct it in your
notes, but this really should be

01:05:17.670 --> 01:05:19.698
radius of the Earth.
Everywhere, here,

01:05:19.698 --> 01:05:22.470
I want to be at a height
h, above the radius of

01:05:22.470 --> 01:05:24.460
the Earth.
So, I put that here.

01:05:24.460 --> 01:05:34.807
Then, I write this as
-GMm/R_E)(1 +

01:05:34.807 --> 01:05:43.413
h/R_E )^(-1).
I just bring the downstairs to

01:05:43.413 --> 01:05:46.190
the upstairs.
Then, remember the wonderful

01:05:46.190 --> 01:05:49.184
formula I told you?
You guys have to know this:

01:05:49.184 --> 01:05:51.593
(1 + x)^(n);
it is approximately 1 +

01:05:51.593 --> 01:05:54.210
nx, if x is very
small;

01:05:54.210 --> 01:05:56.332
x is here,
the height over the radius of

01:05:56.332 --> 01:05:58.039
the Earth, which is obviously
tiny,

01:05:58.039 --> 01:06:04.528
so I can approximate that and I
get U =

01:06:04.528 --> 01:06:14.023
-GMm/R_E times 1 +
GMm/R^(2)_E

01:06:14.023 --> 01:06:17.030
times h.

01:06:21.909 --> 01:06:26.963
This is the potential energy at
the surface of the Earth for a

